<article>
    <h1>The Death Val&#xAD;ley you never knew</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200829/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-29"><time>2020-08-29</time></a>
        - <span>SCIENCE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Death Val­ley – whose name was coined by gold min­ers who lost their way in the area in the win­ter of 1849-1850 – is known for its for­bid­ding heat and arid­ity. A high but yet-to-be of­fi­cial tem­per­a­ture of 54.4 deg C was recorded near Fur­nace Creek Vis­i­tor Cen­tre in the val­ley at 3.41pm on Aug 16. If ver­i­fied, it will be the high­est tem­per­a­ture recorded on earth since 1931. And yet, con­trary to pop­u­lar be­lief, this seem­ingly in­hos­pitable place is far from life­less.</p>

